"{\"uid\": \"salon.com-2024-08-02-italian-olympic-boxer-apologizes-as-transvestigation-against-opponent-spreads\", \"text\": \"Italian Olympic boxer Angela Carini is standing with Algerian opponent Imane Khelif, a cisgender woman who faced a barrage of attacks from far-right\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ctransvestigators\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009donline.  Carini took to Italian newspaper Gazzetta dello Sport to issue an apology to Khelif, who defeated her in a 46-second match on Thursday, inciting attacks on the boxer who once failed a now-discredited \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cgender test\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d conducted by the International Boxing Association.  Carini, who initially refused to shake hands with Khelif, said she didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t intend to disrespect the athlete.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI want to apologize to her and everyone else. I was angry because my Olympics had gone up in smoke,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d shereportedlysaid, adding that she didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t agree with the transphobic discourse launched by the defeat. \\\"I am sorry for my opponent, too. If the IOC said she can fight, I respect that decision.\\\"  While former PresidentDonald Trump,VP nominee JD Vance, author JK Rowling, and the rest of the far-right transphobic internet swarm pushed unsubstantiated claims against Khelif, the IOC and others quickly quashed rumors that Khelif, who was born as a woman, was transgender.  Critics of the anti-trans movement, including left-wing commentator Hasan Piker, say the incident is emblematic of the extremes that transphobic rhetoric leads to, posing threats of violence even for cisgender women.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTransphobia is a legitimate brain disease that eventually causes people to suspect EVERYONE of being trans,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Pikerwrotein a post to X. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThis harms trans women AND ciswomen.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026 Salon.com, LLC. Reproduction of material from any Salon pages without written permission is strictly prohibited. SALON \\u00c2\\u00ae is registered in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office as a trademark of Salon.com, LLC. Associated Press articles: Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2016 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.  DMCA Policy  By subscribing, you agree that Salon will automatically charge you at the then-current rate (currently $9.95/month or $95/year) each month/year until you cancel. Log in to your account anytime to cancel prior to renewal date and avoid future charges.  Your current signup type is\"}"